# rocknix_abl kit provenance

abl_signed-SM8550.elf is NOT committed here — the PKGBUILD fetches it from the
official ROCKNIX ABL release, pinned by tag + sha512:

  release:  https://github.com/ROCKNIX/abl/releases/tag/v1.1.5
  asset:    rocknix-abl-v1.1.5.tar.gz
  tarball sha512: dffcefb9975880f1e54da3538bac0598b67761af662a4e7365e36c81ba109797
                  ff44a5d23deea0a4999deae185f5bc24609e4c6037d68fc916ffeaaa6492234e
  abl_signed-SM8550.elf sha256 (release's own sidecar, re-checked in prepare()):
                  efa890e9000f462ac3f2d74ac2f40a22d82bb7f7645639296977dc638d00876b

It is ROCKNIX's patched, test-key-signed build of the Qualcomm ABL (edk2
LinuxLoader, BSD-3-Clause) for the SM8550 family — the bootloader that scans
for the FAT labeled ROCKNIX and boots /KERNEL (an Android boot image, board
dtb selected by board id). One elf serves every SM8550 board (RP6, AYN
Odin 2 / Mini / Portal); ROCKNIX keys the artifact by SoC.

The four kit files (README, flash_abl.sh.template, backup_abl.sh,
restore_backup_abl.sh) are VERBATIM copies from the ROCKNIX distribution repo,
packages/tools/rocknix-abl/sources/ (GPL-2.0 tree), as pinned by our `make
sync` snapshot. The PKGBUILD's %DEVICE% -> SM8550 substitution in
flash_abl.sh reproduces their package.mk. Vendored (4 tiny files, change
rarely) rather than fetched or synced; diff them against the ROCKNIX tree
when advancing the sync pin.

Version coupling: the ABL version ROCKNIX pins for the SoC lives in their
packages/tools/rocknix-abl/package.mk (PKG_VERSION). Ours (_ablver in the
PKGBUILD) should track it — the ABL defines the boot contract the sm8550
profile assumes (FAT label, /KERNEL boot image, board-id dtb select), so a
mismatched pair is the thing to avoid. v1.1.5 = their pin AND the latest
release as of 2026-07-23.

The kit's job is FIRST INSTALL from stock Android: the user copies
rocknix_abl/ off the SD's boot FAT to Android internal storage, runs
backup_abl.sh (saves the stock abl_a/abl_b next to the scripts — tell users
to copy those .img backups OFF the device; an install-to-internal later
wipes userdata and the backup with it), then flash_abl.sh, both as root.
restore_backup_abl.sh is the road back to a fully stock device. pocknix
never flashes the ABL itself — no alpm hook, no updateabl equivalent.
